item.title: Engineering Management Is Dying
item.dc:creator: jvangorp
item.description: Engineering management, as a distinct competence, is disappearing from the software world. It’s been undone by both technological and cultural change; by years of failure applying standard project management techniques where they don’t belong, and equally, from the widespread acceptance of Agile (however you define it) as THE one-size-fits-all way to do things. But mostly, it’s been undone by a continuing erosion of responsibility accorded to managers.

item.title: A Better Project Model than the "Waterfall" - Jeff Gothelf - Harvard Business Review
item.dc:creator: chris.heisel
item.description:
"In software development, reality bats last." What he means is that no matter how optimistic a team may be about the product it's building, the only thing that will prove the project successful or not is the reality of real customers using it to solve real problems.
When the project timeline elapses, the team may not have shipped as many features as they would have in the old waterfall way but those they did ship are the right features. Working with hypotheses instead of requirements allows the team to figure out which solutions have the most promise of success while minimizing the amount of time spent developing ideas that are wrong.
